The Americas
---------------
[1] Brazil (Ceara)
Date: Thu 25 Sep 2014
Source: O Povo Online [in Portuguese, trans. Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ, edited]
http://www.opovo.com.br/app/opovo/cotidiano/2014/09/25/noticiasjornalcotidiano,3320239/ceara-registra-92-dos-casos-confirmados-de-sarampo-no-pais-em-2014.shtml


Although vaccination is available in all health centers in Fortaleza [the capital], the state of Ceara reported 92 percent of the 401 cases of measles recorded in Brazil from January to the beginning of September [2014]. There were 370 confirmed cases, 142 of them in the capital and the rest in 20 other cities. The incidence rate of the disease reached more than 300 per 100 000 inhabitants in some municipalities. There were no deaths due to complications of the disease.

According to the [5 Sep 2014] epidemiological bulletin of the Ceara Department of Health (SESA), the remaining cases were reported from the states of Pernambuco (24) and Sao Paulo (7). The next bulletin is expected this week.

In Ceara, the city of Massape (272 km/169 miles from Fortaleza) recorded 92 cases of the disease, with an incidence rate of 246.6; Uruburetama (127 km/79 mi from the capital) had 61 cases and an incidence rate of 300.7 per 100 000 inhabitants. Statisticians report that 98 suspected cases are still being investigated in 11 municipalities of Ceara.

The 1st case in Fortaleza was a doctor who was working in the area comprising Regional Secretariat II. "Every time a vaccination campaign does not reach 95-100 percent of the population, it creates these pockets of susceptible people," comments Vanessa Soldateli, the director of immunization of the Municipal Health Department (SMS).

According to the report, the age groups most affected by measles were children between 6 months and one year (63 cases), adults between 20 and 29 years (75 cases), and young people aged 15 to 19 years (54 cases). Soldateli explains that in the capital alone, babies accounted for 44 percent of cases. "Children under one year are not vaccinated because it is not indicated in the routine vaccination schedule for the 1st year of life. But in an outbreak situation, you ignore it because the benefit is greater than any loss," she says.

The coordinator of Health Promotion and Protection of SESA, Marcio Garcia, says that intensification of prevention work in the interior had begun in the 1st semester of 2014. "We managed to contain the outbreak in Uruburetama, and the last case there was reported in June [2014]. In the region of Sobral, where Massape is located, the situation has started to improve, but we [must remain alert] because neighboring municipalities, from other regions of the state are beginning to report suspected cases," says Garcia.

[Byline: Sara Oliveira]

--
